05462nam a22007695i 9780226454573DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264545737 a10.7208/97802264545732doi  a(DE-B1597)523308  a(OCoLC)475003206  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBF575.H27 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a152.4/2072222/eng00aMeasuring the Subjective Well-Being of Nations :bNational Accounts of Time Use and Well-Being /ced. by Alan B. Krueger. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b1 halftone, 30 line drawings, 74 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction and Overview -- t1. National Time Accounting: The Currency of Life -- t2. That Which Makes Life Worthwhile -- t3. Measuring National Well- Being -- t4. National Time Accounting and National Economic Accounting -- t5. Measuring Real Income with Leisure and Household Production -- t6. Well-Being Measurement and Public Policy -- t7. International Evidence on Well- Being -- t8. Thoughts on “National Time Accounting: The Currency of Life” -- t9. Rejoinder -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSurely everyone wants to know the source of happiness, and indeed, economists and social scientists are increasingly interested in the study and effects of subjective well-being. Putting forward a rigorous method and new data for measuring, comparing, and analyzing the relationship between well-being and the way people spend their time—across countries, demographic groups, and history—this book will help set the agenda of research and policy for decades to come. It does so by introducing a system of National Time Accounting (NTA), which relies on individuals’ own evaluations of their emotional experiences during various uses of time, a distinct departure from subjective measures such as life satisfaction and objective measures such as the Gross Domestic Product. A distinguished group of contributors here summarize the NTA method, provide illustrative findings about well-being based on NTA, and subject the approach to a rigorous conceptual and methodological critique that advances the field. As subjective well-being is topical in economics, psychology, and other social sciences, this book should have cross-disciplinary appeal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHappinessvCongresses. 0aHappinessxCongresses. 0aLifevCongresses. 0aLifexCongresses. 0aNational characteristicsvCongresses. 0aNational characteristicsxCongresses. 0aQuality of lifevCongresses. 0aQuality of lifexCongresses. 0aWell-beingvCongresses. 0aWell-beingxCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBlanchflower, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurst, Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahneman, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrueger, Alan B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrueger, Alan B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLandefeld, J. Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLayard, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoewenstein, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordhaus, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchkade, Da